re 1220","Crokerton, Essex, England":"Essex, England","Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England":"Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheadle, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Coleville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Colleville in Seine-Maritime, France, named with the Scandinavian personal name <i>Koli</i> (see   Cole   2) + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement, village’. The Scottish branch of the family were descended from Philip <i>de Colville</i>, who came to Scotland as a household knight of kings Malcolm IV (1153–65) and William ‘the Lion’ (1165–1214)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cole","meanings":["English: usually from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, <i>Coll(e)</i>, <i>Coul(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nicol</i> (see   Nichol   and   Nicholas  ), a common personal name from the mid 13th century onward. English families with this name migrated to Scotland and to Ulster (especially Fermanagh).","English: occasionally perhaps from a different (early) Middle English personal name <i>Col</i>, of native English or Scandinavian origin. Old English <i>Cola</i> was originally a nickname from Old English <i>col</i> ‘coal’ in the sense ‘coal-black (of hair), swarthy’ and is the probable source of most of the examples in Domesday Book. In the northern and eastern counties of England settled by Vikings in the 10th and 11th centuries, alternative sources are Old Norse <i>Kolr</i> and <i>Koli</i> (either from a nickname ‘the swarthy one’ or a short form of names in <i>Kol-</i>), and Old Norse <i>Kollr</i> (from a nickname, perhaps ‘the bald one’).","English: nickname for someone with swarthy skin or black hair, from Middle English <i>col</i>, coul(e) ‘charcoal, coal’ (Old English <i>col</i>)."]},{"name":"Colvin","meanings":["Scottish and Irish (Donegal, Antrim): variant of   Colville  , probably reflecting a local pronunciation. The name was taken to Ulster in the 17th century.","Manx: if not identical with 1, perhaps from the Old Norse personal name <i>Kolbeinn</i>, with /v/ substituted for /b/.","English: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Colwin</i>, <i>Colvin</i>, which may be a borrowing into English of a Welsh name whose modern form is <i>Collwyn</i> ‘white’, or of <i>colwyn</i> ‘doe, puppy, pet dog’, or of the placename <i>Colwyn</i> (Denbighshire, Radnorshire)."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Coleville was born in 1170, in Cheadle, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Coleville, was 21 and her mother, Alice Arcy, was 17. She married Ralph le Brett I. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died before 1220."},"et":{"1170–Bef. 1220":"1170–enne 1220","1170–1220":"1170–1220","1170–1235":"1170–1235","1195–1220":"1195–1220","1200–1252":"1200–1252","1210–1238":"1210–1238","1195–1248":"1195–1248","1150–1205":"1150–1205","1153–1210":"1153–1210","1220":"1220","1153":"1153","1252":"1252","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1205":"1205","1238":"1238","1248":"1248","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","about 1205":"umbes 1205","1210":"1210","Bef. 1220":"enne 1220","Crokerton, Essex, England":"Essex, England","Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England":"Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheadle, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1170–Bef. 1220":"1170–ennen vuotta 1220","1170–1220":"1170–1220","1170–1235":"1170–1235","1195–1220":"1195–1220","1200–1252":"1200–1252","1210–1238":"1210–1238","1195–1248":"1195–1248","1150–1205":"1150–1205","1153–1210":"1153–1210","1220":"1220","1153":"1153","1252":"1252","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1205":"1205","1238":"1238","1248":"1248","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","about 1205":"noin 1205","1210":"1210","Bef. 1220":"ennen vuotta 1220","Crokerton, Essex, England":"Essex, England","Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England":"Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cheadle, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1170–Bef. 1220":"1170–avant 1220","1170–1220